"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417176","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>A large number of Government and publicly‑funded bodies subscribe to Met Office services. Revenue from this sector in 2014-15 was approximately £187m, broken down as follows: (a) Public Weather Service - £114m (b) Defence - £33m and (c) Government strategic sectors - £40m. The terms of service provision are subject to periodic review and renegotiation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Commercial revenue was £33m in 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Met Office expenditure on research and development is detailed in its annual report and accounts. The amount spent in the last 5 years is set out below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9206 ; 9211","2015-09-15T16:24:59.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417176/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417176/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Met Office: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which Government and publicly-funded bodies and agencies subscribe to Met Office services; what the value is of each such subscription; and what the termination date is of each such subscription.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417177","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Government expects to lay amendments to the Education (Student Support) Regulations 2011 later this year and publish an Equality Analysis when the Regulations are laid. The Equality Analysis will include an assessment of the potential impacts of the changes.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-15T15:57:14.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417177/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417177/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will make an assessment of the likely effect of the abolition of student maintenance grants on widening participation in higher education.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417178","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>A large number of Government and publicly‑funded bodies subscribe to Met Office services. Revenue from this sector in 2014-15 was approximately £187m, broken down as follows: (a) Public Weather Service - £114m (b) Defence - £33m and (c) Government strategic sectors - £40m. The terms of service provision are subject to periodic review and renegotiation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Commercial revenue was £33m in 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Met Office expenditure on research and development is detailed in its annual report and accounts. The amount spent in the last 5 years is set out below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p>43</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9206 ; 9210","2015-09-15T16:24:59.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417178/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417178/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Met Office: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the value is of the contracts currently delivered by the Met Office to commercial organisations.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417179","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>At present there are 4 Met Office staff on secondment to Government departments and agencies and 10 seconded to other publicly-funded bodies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No Met Office staff are on secondment to the armed forces. At present 52 staff are members of the Mobile Met Unit, a sponsored RAF reserve unit of meteorological specialists. There are 192 Met Office staff based at military sites in the UK and overseas.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9204","2015-09-16T13:22:13.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417179/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417179/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Met Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many Met Office staff are on secondment to the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417180","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-24","<p>The BBC’s decision not to shortlist the Met Office for its next contract was a commercial decision by the BBC and was communicated by Met Office to my officials and myself as soon as they became aware that they were not being selected for the next stage of the procurement. The ending of the contract in autumn 2016 is not expected to have significant budgetary implications.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since the communication of the decision I and my officials have been in dialogue with the Met Office and colleagues elsewhere in government in connection with National Severe Weather Warning service, and in turn with the BBC. The Weather Services Agreement between the Met Office and BBC does not include a research element.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9205 ; 9208 ; 9223","2015-09-24T10:08:08.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417180/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417180/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","BBC: Met Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the budgetary implications for the Met Office of the termination of its contract with the BBC.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417181","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-24","<p>The BBC’s decision not to shortlist the Met Office for its next contract was a commercial decision by the BBC and was communicated by Met Office to my officials and myself as soon as they became aware that they were not being selected for the next stage of the procurement. The ending of the contract in autumn 2016 is not expected to have significant budgetary implications.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since the communication of the decision I and my officials have been in dialogue with the Met Office and colleagues elsewhere in government in connection with National Severe Weather Warning service, and in turn with the BBC. The Weather Services Agreement between the Met Office and BBC does not include a research element.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9205 ; 9208 ; 9209","2015-09-24T10:08:08.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417181/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417181/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Met Office: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of the funds generated by the Met Office's contract with the BBC was spent on research in the last 12 months; and what research projects undertaken by the Met Office in that period the BBC has (a) collaborated with or (b) participated in.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417182","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Met Office collaborates with a number of universities and research organisations in the UK and overseas to advance the science and skills in meteorology, climate science and related subjects. This involves the placement of scientists between the Met Office and these bodies. Visits can be for short or longer periods of time, but are not generally recorded as formal secondments. During 2014-15, 149 scientists were recorded as visiting the Met Office for collaborative purposes. Extensive collaboration also takes place in the writing of scientific papers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Met Office records of current and previous formal secondments to universities and research organisations are shown in the table below. It has no record of inward secondments from these organisations in the last 5 years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Secondments</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9225","2015-09-16T13:13:36.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417182/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417182/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Met Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff secondments (a) to and (b) from (i) universities, (ii) research institutes and (iii) research centres the Met Office has in place; and how many such secondments took place in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417183","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Met Office collaborates with a number of universities and research organisations in the UK and overseas to advance the science and skills in meteorology, climate science and related subjects. This involves the placement of scientists between the Met Office and these bodies. Visits can be for short or longer periods of time, but are not generally recorded as formal secondments. During 2014-15, 149 scientists were recorded as visiting the Met Office for collaborative purposes. Extensive collaboration also takes place in the writing of scientific papers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Met Office records of current and previous formal secondments to universities and research organisations are shown in the table below. It has no record of inward secondments from these organisations in the last 5 years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Secondments</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9224","2015-09-16T13:13:37.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417183/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417183/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Met Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which collaborations with (a) universities, (b) research institutes and (c) research centres the Met Office is engaged in; when each such secondment is due to expire; and how many such collaborations have been discontinued since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417184","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Medical Research Council (MRC) is one of the main agencies through which the Government supports medical and clinical research.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The most recent information available on the MRC’s expenditure on cancer research is set out in the table. The data includes research into the biology, causes, prevention, diagnosis and treatment of cancer as well as research on outcomes. A breakdown showing expenditure on research directly related to treatment is not currently available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>MRC spend on cancer research (£m)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£107.7m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£112.1m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£ 95.8m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£ 79.9m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£ 76.2m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong>Source:</strong> National Cancer Research Institute (NCRI) Cancer Research Database (calendar year figures).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-15T15:21:28.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417184/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417184/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Cancer: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Medical Research Council has spent on research projects relating to the treatment of cancer in each financial year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417185","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>The Department will not be publishing the McKinsey work on the grounds that to do so would be likely to reduce the Government’s ability to protect the policy-making process and maintain the delivery of effective Government.</p><p>The Department does not hold centrally a record of all external reports, or policy evaluations, that have been carried out by external organisations for the Department and its Agencies. To produce such a list dating back to May 2010/ financial year 2010-11 respectively would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9587","2015-09-17T09:29:55.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417185/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417185/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what policy evaluations have been carried out by external organisations for his Department and its agencies in each financial year since 2010-11; whether the output of those evaluations was published; which organisation carried out each such evaluation; and what the value of each contract to provide that evaluation was.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417186","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Government commissioned an extensive research project into perceived pregnancy and maternity discrimination in Great Britain. The research was jointly managed and funded by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Equalities and Human Rights Commission, supported by the Government Equalities Office. This research is the largest ever study of pregnancy and maternity-related discrimination conducted in Great Britain. Interim results published in July 2015 reported that 18% of employers found arranging and managing maternity cover difficult to manage. Final results, including how experiences vary by employer size, are due to be published in autumn 2015. The Government will respond when the final results are available.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-15T14:20:02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417186/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417186/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Maternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what research and evidence he has (a) assessed and (b) commissioned on the management of maternity cover by (i) small and (ii) large employers.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","9215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417187","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>There is extensive guidance for employers on both Gov.uk and the Acas website on the statutory entitlement to maternity leave and pay. The Acas Helpline Online tool provides Q&amp;A for employer and employee customers. The tool contains guidance on the working arrangements for people providing maternity cover and links to more detailed content on establishing fixed term contracts and the way in which employers should manage the process of an employee returning to work following maternity leave.</p><p>Acas also provides web-based guidance on maternity leave and pay, including material on arrangements for keeping in touch with parents on one form of leave or another.</p><p>In the last 12 months (September 2014 to August 2015) 1,997 customers have attended Acas training courses on issues related to working parents, including Maternity, Shared Parental Leave and operating Flexible Working.</p><p>The Acas Helpline takes in the region of 50,000 calls from employers and employees on topics related to maternity, paternity and adoption each year, providing practical guidance and support for customers, including assistance in relation to maternity cover issues.</p><p>Acas plans to review its web guidance on maternity during 2015 and the question of maternity cover will be covered in more detail in future guidance.</p><p>In addition the Equalities and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) has produced a suite of frequently asked questions for employers to assist them in understanding their legal obligations and providing suggestions of good practice in managing pregnancy, maternity leave and return to work.</p><p>EHRC has also produced a toolkit for employers, particularly aimed at smaller employers who do not have an HR function, which contains a stock of pre-prepared letters, check lists and ready-made policy templates. It also allows employers to keep on top of key dates with a date calculator.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-15T14:18:48.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417187/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417187/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Maternity Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what (a) guidance and (b) support his Department provides for employers on the management of maternity cover; and what plans he has to increase such support.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","9216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417188","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has provided grant support of £32M to support three programmes; ASTRAEA 1 and 2 and 3A since 2006.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the ASTRAEA consortium applied for additional support for a £55M collaborative programme via the Aerospace Technology Institute (ATI), requesting a £26M grant. The application was not approved.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work with the ASTRAEA consortium and the wider Unmanned Air Vehicle community on how best to support the development of this market and will consider requests for funding support that deliver value for money for the UK.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-15T15:55:42.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417188/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417188/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what public funding has been allocated to support the Astrea programme; what applications for funds for that programme his Department has received and under which Government programmes; and what plans he has for future funding of that programme.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417189","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Department currently uses the GDP deflators published by the Treasury to remove the effect of inflation from research and development (R&amp;D) spending. The Office for National Statistics carried out some work to develop an R&amp;D deflator; however, this work did not include a forward looking deflator so was not suitable for applying to future expenditure. We have not commissioned any research, but continue to monitor new developments in this area.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-15T16:00:29.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417189/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417189/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what measure of inflation his Department uses for research and development spending; and what research he has (a) commissioned and (b) consulted in forming his policy.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417190","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Chief Scientific Advisers work across departments in partnership with policy makers to ensure the very best in scientific evidence is used in the policy process. Where posts are unfilled, the Government Office for Science works with departments to ensure they have access to the relevant expertise and evidence. The table below contains the current position on CSAs.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><br><p><strong>Dept</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>CSA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Appt. Dates</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>BIS</strong></p></td><td><p>Tim Dafforn</p></td><td><p>July 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>CLG</strong></p></td><td><p>Stephen Aldridge (interim)</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DCMS</strong></p></td><td><p>Vacant</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DECC</strong></p></td><td><p>John Loughhead</p></td><td><p>Oct 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DEFRA</strong></p></td><td><p>Ian Boyd</p></td><td><p>September 2012</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DfE</strong></p></td><td><p>Tim Leunig</p></td><td><p>March 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DfID</strong></p></td><td><p>Chris Whitty</p></td><td><p>June 2009</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DfT</strong></p></td><td><p>Phil Blythe</p></td><td><p>June 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DH</strong></p></td><td><p>Sally Davies</p></td><td><p>June 2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DWP</strong></p></td><td><p>Pui-Ling Li</p></td><td><p>December 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>FCO</strong></p></td><td><p>Robin Grimes</p></td><td><p>February 2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>FSA</strong></p></td><td><p>Guy Poppy</p></td><td><p>August 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>HMT</strong></p></td><td><p>Susan Acland-Hood</p></td><td><p>May 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>HO</strong></p></td><td><p>Bernard Silverman</p></td><td><p>April 2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>MOD</strong></p></td><td><p>Vernon Gibson</p></td><td><p>July 2012</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>National Security</strong></p></td><td><p>Nick Jennings</p></td><td><p>June 2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>MOJ</strong></p></td><td><p>Vacant</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>N.Ireland</strong></p></td><td><p>Vacant</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Scotland</strong></p></td><td><p>Vacant</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Wales</strong></p></td><td><p>Julie Williams</p></td><td><p>September 2013</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-16T15:25:07.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417190/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417190/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, who the chief scientific advisers are; when each such adviser took up their post; and which chief scientific adviser posts currently remain unfilled.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417191","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2015-09-10","<p><del class="ministerial">This information is not available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">The total number of potential tribunal claims for pregnancy-related detriment or dismissal notified to Acas under the early conciliation scheme by individuals in 2014-15 was 1,851. Of these:</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">· 308 were settled by Acas at early conciliation stage and recorded on a COT3 settlement document;</ins></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">· 545 progressed to a tribunal claim being taken, 264 of which were subsequently settled on an Acas COT3 following further conciliation;</ins></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">· 998 were not settled through Acas, but did not progress to a tribunal case.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">An additional 18 notifications were made by employers. Seventeen of these were settled by Acas and the other was neither settled nor progressed to a tribunal.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Government does not have data on the number of private settlements which settled claims before reaching a tribunal. The independently commissioned survey of early conciliation (a sample across all jurisdictions) found that 61 per cent of claimants (and their representatives) who did not settle but decided not to submit a tribunal claim reported that Acas was a factor in their decision.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">Please note: (i) The jurisdictional provided to Acas is only indicative based on the information given by the prospective claimant; (ii) Counted individually there were a total of 1,882 notifications which means that a small number of claimants notified against more than one respondent.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-10T16:40:49.2Z","2015-09-14T09:48:13.74Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417191/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417191/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417191/answer/previousversion/20420","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Pregnancy: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many potential tribunal claims for pregnancy-related detriment or dismissal were notified to Acas under the early conciliation scheme in 2014-15; and how many of those claims (i) were settled by conciliation by Acas, (ii) progressed to a tribunal claim and (iii) were not settled by conciliation by Acas but did not progress to a tribunal case.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","9119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417192","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>More young people from disadvantaged backgrounds are applying to higher education than ever before. 18 year olds from the most disadvantaged areas were 72% more likely to apply to higher education in 2015 than in 2006.</p><p>Since 2012, institutions have been required to take more responsibility for widening participation. Institutions wishing to charge fees above the basic rate must have Access Agreements agreed by independent Director of Fair Access. The amounts institutions expect to spend on widening access through these agreements are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>2019/20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Amount</p><p>£m</p></td><td><p>718.8</p></td><td><p>745.4</p></td><td><p>741.6</p></td><td><p>746.2</p></td><td><p>750.8</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In addition, the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) allocates funding to institutions to help with the additional costs of recruiting and supporting students from disadvantaged backgrounds through the Student Opportunity Allocation. In 2015/16, HEFCE is allocating £364.2m to institutions through the Allocation. In recent grant letters, Ministers have asked HEFCE to prioritise widening participation in their decisions about allocating funding from their block grant.</p><p>Through the Student Opportunity Allocation, the Government has provided £22 million seed-corn funding for the establishment of national networks of collaborative outreach, across 2014-15 and 2015-16. The networks bring together universities to provide a single point of contact for schools and colleges to find out about outreach opportunities for their students and to access information about higher education. There are 35 local and three national networks involving 200 universities and further education colleges. They are reaching 4,300 secondary schools and colleges. From 2016 onwards, funding will be provided by universities themselves.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","9131","2015-09-14T13:23:11.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417192/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417192/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what funding his Department has allocated to encourage students from low-income backgrounds to access higher education in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","9135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417193","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>UK Green Investment Bank plc continues to operate in accordance with its existing remit, applying its rigorous investment criteria in pursuing business opportunities within the United Kingdom across the green sectors in which it is currently active.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-14T09:09:16.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417193/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417193/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the Green Investment Bank will invest in projects (a) according to its existing risk profile and sectoral focus and (b) exclusively in the UK economy during the period in which the Government is discussing privatisation of the Bank with private investors.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","9137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417194","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>As set out in the Code of Practice for the Postcode Address File (PAF®), which was agreed between Royal Mail and the Postal Regulator in May 2010, there is a process in place for the creation of addresses which aims to ensure that every business and house in the UK falling under the Royal Mail’s Universal Service Obligation, has a postal address to enable the delivery of items quickly and accurately.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local Authorities have the responsibility of naming roads and the postal address reflects the details provided by the Local Authorities. Royal Mail applies the postcode to these details which forms the basis of the Royal Mail distribution network. Royal Mail also pays Local Authorities £1 per new address listed in the PAF.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the public sector licence agreement was introduced which gives Local Authorities and Central Government, Emergency Services and Health, free access to the PAF.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the agreed arrangements in place for the creation of addresses for the PAF.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-14T14:48:46.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417194/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417194/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Post Codes: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department, its agencies or Ofcom has made an assessment of (a) the appropriateness of the role of local authorities in the creation of addresses for the Postcode Address File and (b) whether that role constitutes a subsidy to Royal Mail.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417195","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-17","<p>The core Department for Business Innovation and Skills spent the following on carbon offsetting in the last 3 years:</p><p>F/Y 09-10 EDF Trading Ltd - £90063</p><p>F/Y 10-11 RWE Supply &amp; Trade in Switzerland SA - £31496.33</p><p>F/Y 11-12 South Pole Carbon Asset Management Ltd - £2902.72</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-17T09:29:17.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417195/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417195/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417196","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>According to Start-Up Loans Company, of the 32,007 businesses funded to date, 20% have been to 18-24 year olds and 32% to 25-30 year olds. 1527 loans made to 18-24 group and 3273 loans made to 25-30 group are in default. The government is committed to increasing the number of loans to 75,000 by the end of the next Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-15T15:36:57.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417196/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417196/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","New Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many start-up loans the Government has made to young people under the age of (a) 25 and (b) 30 in each year since the commencement of the start-up loan scheme; what the current default rate is on such loans; and what estimate he has made of how many more such loans will be made over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","9127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417197","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-15","<p>We are currently consulting on options for freezing the £21,000 post-2012 repayment threshold. The consultation is open until 14 October.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-15T15:58:38.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417197/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417197/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-07","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he has received about retrospective changes to the terms and conditions of student loan repayments.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","9129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417198","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>Sir John Chilcot is paid a fee of £790 for each day worked. His Committee colleagues are paid £565 for each day they work. According to the Inquiry’s website, remuneration for the Committee and its advisers totalled £119,300 for the Financial year 2014/15.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-14T16:10:53.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417198/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417198/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what fees were paid to Sir John Chilcot for his work on the Iraq Inquiry in each quarter from January 2014 to the end of June 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","9090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417199","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>Government is committed to making digital inclusion part of wider policy, programmes and digital services. Investment has been made in the national super-fast broadband roll out and funding for a basic digital skills programme that will reach 1 million digitally excluded people over 5 years and £7.4m has also been committed to fund free wifi and internet access for libraries in England.</p><p> </p><p>Digital inclusion is tracked through data collected and published by organisations such the ONS (internet use) and BBC/Go ON UK (basic digital skills). We will continue to monitor progress on this basis.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-10T14:46:47.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417199/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417199/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has for tackling digital exclusion over this Parliament; and if he will publish the data that his Department collects on digital exclusion.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417200","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Cabinet Office processes personal data in accordance with the principles set out in Schedule 1 of the Data Protection Act 1998. The Cabinet Office’s entry on the Data Protection Register is available on the Information Commissioner’s Office website at <a href="https://ico.org.uk/ESDWebPages/DoSearch?reg=163896" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/ESDWebPages/DoSearch?reg=163896</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-10T15:05:27.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417200/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417200/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the principles his Department follows for handling and sharing the data of members of the public.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417201","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-15","<p>Mike Bracken is the Government Chief Data Officer. Future appointments will be announced in the normal way.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-15T16:21:55.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417201/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417201/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Cabinet Office: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he plans to appoint a Chief Data Officer; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417202","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>In September 2012, the UK volunteered to be peer-reviewed on our policies and mechanisms to build national and community resilience to natural disasters. The review was carried out by the UN Office for Disaster Relief Reduction, the European Commission and the OECD, and funding was provided by the EU. Their report, <em>Peer Review Report: United Kingdom, 2013: Building Resilience to Disasters</em>, <em>Assessing the implementation of the Hyogo Framework for Action</em> (2005-2010) is available on the UNISDR website at <a href="http://www.unisdr.org/files/32996_32996hfaukpeerreview20131.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.unisdr.org/files/32996_32996hfaukpeerreview20131.pdf</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-14T16:47:01.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417202/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417202/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Cabinet Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what policy evaluations have been carried out by external organisations for his Department and its agencies in each financial year since 2010-11; whether the output of those evaluations was published; which organisation carried out each such evaluation; and what the value of each contract to provide that evaluation was.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417203","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Cabinet Office’s expenditure to date in respect of carbon offsetting arising from Official and Ministerial air travel was as follows;</p><p>2014-15 £717.34p payment was made to Carbon Footprint Ltd</p><p>2013-14 £1572.78p payment was made to Carbon Footprint Ltd</p><p>2012-13 £782.00p payment was made to South Pole Carbon Asset Management Ltd.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-14T16:12:14.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417203/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417203/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Cabinet Office: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Department spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417204","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Average Working Days Lost (AWDL) per staff year in the Civil Service has fallen from 8.8 days in 2010 to 7.4 days in 2015. This shows we are making good progress in reducing sickness absence in the Civil Service, and we are continuing to monitor and actively manage staff attendance.</p><p><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year ending</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average Working Days Lost per staff year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31st March 2010</p></td><td><p>8.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31st March 2013</p></td><td><p>7.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31st March 2014</p></td><td><p>7.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31st March 2015</p></td><td><p>7.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-09-10T15:07:48.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417204/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417204/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-07","Civil Servants: Lost Working Days","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the average working days lost per full time equivalent member of staff was as a result of sick days and absences in the Civil Service in (a) 2013, (b) 2014 and (c) 2015.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","9241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417205","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-15","<p>Information on policy evaluations carried out by external organisations is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-15T16:51:15.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417205/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417205/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Treasury: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what policy evaluations have been carried out by external organisations for his Department and its agencies in each financial year since 2010-11; whether the output of those evaluations was published; which organisation carried out each such evaluation; and what the value of each contract to provide that evaluation was.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417206","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government takes all types of fraud, including those operating through telephones, extremely seriously. The Government is continuing to work closely with the police, Financial Fraud Action UK, and the British Bankers’ Association on initiatives to tackle fraud. Last year, during the ‘Know Fraud, No Fraud’ campaign, UK banks, building societies and card issuers, with the support of the police, published a Joint Declaration explaining the requests they would never ask of customers over the phone. This includes never asking a customer to authorise the transfer of funds to a new account.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government also recommends that any person affected by telephone scams such as vishing, formally report their case to Action Fraud. Action Fraud is a Government supported specialist fraud reporting and advice service operated by the City of London Police. When a serious threat or a new type of fraud is identified, Action Fraud places an alert on its website with advice for individuals to protect themselves from becoming victims. Members of the public can sign up to receive these alerts by email.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom, the communications regulator in the UK, has worked closely with the Metropolitan Police Service, Action Fraud and landline providers to prevent criminals exploiting phone lines to trick and defraud members of the public. All landline providers have now reduced the time a call remains open after one party hangs up down to two seconds. This makes it much more difficult for criminals to exploit phone lines in this way.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-11T11:06:47.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417206/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417206/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Bank Services: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to address telephone scamming related to banking services.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417207","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>While Greece remains in the euro, its financial stability is the responsibility of the euro area. The Government has secured a deal that protects UK taxpayers from any risk from financing euro area bailouts now and in the future. This deal gives legal force to the commitment secured in 2010 that UK taxpayers would not be drawn into a euro area bailout.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-14T14:47:26.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417207/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417207/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Loans: Greece","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will continue to ensure that the UK does not contribute to the EU bailout package for Greece.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417208","HM Treasury","false","2015-10-15","<p>HM Treasury spent the following totals on Carbon Offsetting in each of the last three years:</p><p>13/14 – £37,140.00</p><p>12/13 – £36,720.00</p><p>11/12 – £37,980.00</p><p>All Carbon Credits were purchased from the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-10-15T16:22:44.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417208/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417208/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Treasury: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417209","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have regular meetings with departments in which a wide range of issues are discussed as part of the process of policy development. However we do not disclose details of confidential discussions between Ministers or advice received from civil servants.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-11T13:10:58.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417209/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417209/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Government Departments: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his Department and the Government Chief Scientific Adviser had with Departments in advance of decisions to cut departmental research budgets or expenditure since May 2010; and on what dates each such discussion took place with each such department.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417210","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-15","<p>Enterprise Zones have reported that they have attracted over 19,000 jobs since they started in 2012.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the proportion of jobs at each Enterprise Zone which have been moved to other locations is not available. Applications for new Enterprise Zones are not approved where there is considered to be a high likelihood that existing businesses will transfer to the site from neighbouring areas.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-09-15T12:48:03.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417210/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417210/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Enterprise Zones: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many new jobs have been created in each Enterprise Zone in each financial year since 2010-11; and what estimate he has made of the proportion of jobs at each Enterprise Zone which have been moved to other locations.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417211","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-15","<p>The 24 Enterprise Zones that have been established in England since 2012 had by December 2014 provided 18,949 jobs, attracted £2.2 billion of private investment, and attracted over 540 new businesses. We continue to review all available evidence on the efficacy and impact of Enterprise Zones, including from previous programmes in the United Kingdom and abroad.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-09-15T13:22:24.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417211/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417211/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Enterprise Zones: Job Creation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what research he has (a) commissioned and (b) examined on the effect of Enterprise Zones on investment and job creation in other neighbouring localities.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417212","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ contract with SYNNEX-Concentrix UK Limited provides additional capacity to review and correct tax credit claims that are potentially based on incorrect information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Full details of the contractual arrangements can be found at <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</a></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-10T14:53:24.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417212/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417212/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Revenue and Customs: Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people have been contacted on behalf of HM Revenue and Customs by Concentrix; and for what purpose they were so contacted.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","9146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417213","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Government has sought to strike the appropriate balance and ensure that this policy allows the family home to be passed onto the next generation but is also affordable. Around 80% of estates with both a residence and an inheritance tax liability are expected to be in a position to benefit from the nil rate band.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-11T13:45:36.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417213/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417213/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Inheritance Tax: Eligibility","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will extend eligibility for the main residence nil rate band of inheritance tax to non-direct descendants.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","9086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417214","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-15","<p>I refer the honourable gentleman to the answer provided to him on 6 July 2015 (4460). No such discussions have been had on this subject, as the likelihood of the UK Government’s support package being called upon is remote, and there will be no spending by the UK Government unless it is called upon.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I would also refer the honourable gentleman to the written statement made by Rory Stewart MP on 7 September 2015, reference HCWS175, which provides further information on the project.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-09-15T16:50:09.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417214/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417214/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Thames Tideway Tunnel","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on potential Barnett consequentials arising from the Thames Tideway Tunnel project.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","9088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417215","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-16","<p>My rt. hon. Friends, the Home Secretary (Theresa May) and the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government (Greg Clark), are leading a Joint Committee to expand the existing Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme to resettle up to 20,000 Syrians in need of protection during this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>We will work with the local government sector, devolved administrations, the voluntary and community sector, faith communities and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to put in place the necessary arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>My rt. hon. Friend, the Home Secretary provided an update to the House today.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","9125","2015-09-16T16:03:25.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417215/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417215/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Government plans to provide additional funding to local authorities to assist them to provide support to Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","9124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417216","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-16","<p>My rt. hon. Friends, the Home Secretary (Theresa May) and the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government (Greg Clark), are leading a Joint Committee to expand the existing Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme to resettle up to 20,000 Syrians in need of protection during this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>We will work with the local government sector, devolved administrations, the voluntary and community sector, faith communities and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to put in place the necessary arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>My rt. hon. Friend, the Home Secretary provided an update to the House today.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","9124","2015-09-16T16:03:25.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417216/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417216/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the capacity of local authorities to provide support for refugees from Syria.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","9125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417217","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-10","<p>My Department meets with a variety of stakeholders, including firms, about a wide range of matters in the course of its daily business.</p><p> </p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings and those of the Permanent Secretary with external organisations are published on-line here:<br><br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data</strong></a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-permanent-secretary-data-2014#history" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-permanent-secretary-data-2014#history</strong></a></p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-09-10T14:40:39.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417217/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417217/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Department for Communities and Local Government: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what meetings his Department has had with (a) Dart Energy, (b) Igas Energy, (c) Cuadrilla Resources, (d) INEOS Group, (e) Rathlin Energy and (f) Addison Project in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","9122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417218","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-15","<p>We made a commitment in the Summer Budget to reduce social rents in England by one per cent a year for four years from April 2016. This will help protect tenants from rising housing costs whilst protecting taxpayers from the rising costs of subsidising rents through housing benefit. We are confident that local authorities and private registered providers will be able to find and make efficiencies to accommodate the new rent settlement and we remain committed to delivering 275,000 affordable homes over the course of this Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-09-15T11:39:42.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417218/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417218/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effects of changes in the Summer Budget 2015 to the level of rents paid by social tenants on the construction of new social housing.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","9106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417219","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Government has published a policy statement on Part 2 of the Localism Act 2011 concerning the handling of EU infractions and localism. This sets out arrangements for apportioning of fines in relation to infractions of EU legislation, should this be necessary. The UK is working towards the achievement of the EU target to recycle 50% of household waste by 2020 which means the issue of potential fines does not arise.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-10T15:35:48.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417219/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417219/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Domestic Waste: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how she plans to apportion proposed fines relating to the target in the EU Waste Framework Directive to recycle 50 per cent of household waste by 2020 between local authorities.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","9232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417220","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Waste &amp; Resources Action Programme is funded by Government to undertake research and offer advice and support on recycling, including information and guidance to help Local Authorities deliver waste and recycling services. The Government has no plans to issue additional guidance.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-10T08:42:57.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417220/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417220/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Domestic Waste: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to issue guidance to local authorities on the EU Waste Framework Directive requiring them to recycle 50 per cent of household waste by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","9228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417221","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-10","<p>Defra has no plans to set recycling targets at a waste disposal or waste collection authority level. These targets are set at the UK level.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-10T15:33:14.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417221/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417221/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Domestic Waste: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department plans to implement the target to recycle 50 per cent of household waste by 2020 set in the EU Waste Framework Directive at a waste disposal authority or waste collection authority level.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","9229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417222","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Budget in March 2015 confirmed that the standard and lower rates of Landfill Tax will increase in line with RPI, rounded to the nearest 5 pence, from April 2016. Further decisions on Landfill Tax rates will be made at Budget 2016.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-10T14:50:46.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417222/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417222/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-07","Landfill Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to reintroduce the landfill tax escalator.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","9230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417223","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-17","<p>The attached table lists the policy evaluations carried out by DCLG since 2010-11.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-09-17T15:50:31.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417223/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417223/answer","9244 Umunna.pdf","Evaluation Projects in DCLG  - 2010-2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417223/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Department for Communities and Local Government: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what policy evaluations have been carried out by external organisations for his Department and its agencies in each financial year since 2010-11; whether the output of those evaluations was published; which organisation carried out each such evaluation; and what the value of each contract to provide that evaluation was.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417224","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-16","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government spent the following amounts on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years, and with the following companies:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Company</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£464</p></td><td><p>RWE Supply and Trading Switzerland SA</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£29</p></td><td><p>EDF Trading Ltd.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£835</p></td><td><p>South Pole Carbon Asset Management</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department undertakes its carbon offsetting by purchasing Certified Emissions Reduction credits through the Government Carbon Offsetting Facility.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-09-16T15:57:50.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417224/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417224/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Department for Communities and Local Government: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417225","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-15","<p>Analysts in my Department monitor the buy to let market on a regular basis. Their analysis and estimates for the sector are based on data the Department has purchased from the Council of Mortgage Lenders. This is a private database with commercial in confidence data.</p><p> </p><p>Officials in my Department also have a wide range of meetings with lenders (both professional bodies such as Council for Mortgage Lender and Building Society Association) to monitor the buy to let market.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-09-15T11:38:33.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417225/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417225/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-07","Housing Stock: Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to monitor availability of homes in the Buy to Let category in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417226","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-10","<p>The most recent waste from households recycling rate for England in the 12 months to the end of December 2014 was 44.8 per cent.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information about the percentage of household waste recycled by each Local Authority in England for the financial year 2013/14 was published in November 2014 and can be found at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env18-local-authority-collected-waste-annual-results-tables" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env18-local-authority-collected-waste-annual-results-tables</a>. This information is also attached.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-10T09:50:51.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417226/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417226/answer","LA and Regional Spreadsheet 2013-4.xlsx","LA and Regional Spreadsheet 2013-4","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417226/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-07","Domestic Waste: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of household waste each local authority recycles.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","9231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417227","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-15","<p>We pay an annual fee of £1290 as part of the Government's CRC (Carbon Reduction Commitment) Energy Efficiency Scheme. Payments are made to the Environment Agency.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-15T09:27:25.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417227/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417227/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417228","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-14","<p>Since 2010-11 the Department has commissioned the following policy evaluations from external organisations.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Title</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Published</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Meta-evaluation of the impacts and legacy of the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games</p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td><td><p>Grant Thornton</p></td><td><p>£1,400,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The UK's National Broadband Scheme - an independent evaluation report</p></td><td><p>Yes</p></td><td><p>Oxera</p></td><td><p>£117,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold information on evaluations commissioned by its arm’s length bodies centrally.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-14T14:25:38.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417228/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417228/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what policy evaluations have been carried out by external organisations for his Department and its agencies in each financial year since 2010-11; whether the output of those evaluations was published; which organisation carried out each such evaluation; and what the value of each contract to provide that evaluation was.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417229","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-09-11","<p>A decision on whether to undertake Part II of the Leveson Inquiry will not take place until after all criminal investigations and trials related to Part I are concluded. They are still ongoing.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-09-11T13:30:40.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417229/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417229/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-09-07","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he expects part two of the Leveson Inquiry, examining allegations of police corruption and the relationships between newspaper organisations and the police, prosecuting authorities and relevant regulatory bodies to take place; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","9096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417230","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-10","<p>Information on policy evaluations carried out by external organisations is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-09-10T16:28:22.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417230/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417230/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Ministry of Defence: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what policy evaluations have been carried out by external organisations for his Department and its agencies in each financial year since 2010-11; whether the output of those evaluations was published; which organisation carried out each such evaluation; and what the value of each contract to provide that evaluation was.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","9246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417231","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence has spent the following on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Budget Year</p></td><td><p>Offset Costs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£11,611</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>£17,829.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p>Offsets for 2013-14 and 2014-15 were purchased together and cannot be separated.</p><p> </p><p>Payments in respect of the carbon offsetting were made to the Carbon Footprint Ltd via the Crown Commercial Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-09-10T16:30:32.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417231/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417231/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Ministry of Defence: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department spent on carbon offsetting in each of the last three years; and to which companies payments in respect of carbon offsetting were made in each such year.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","9166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417232","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-10","<p>Some 500 local staff are eligible to apply for relocation to the UK under the Ex Gratia Redundancy scheme, of which over 170 local staff are now residing in the UK along with their families. In addition to the redundancy scheme our intimidation policy supports all staff, regardless of role or employment duration, who may be facing security risks as a result of their work with British Forces.</p><p>The UK is the only nation with a permanent team including trained investigation officers in country to investigate claims of intimidation. These experts thoroughly and professionally investigate all claims of intimidation and have provided support to over 200 former local staff including bespoke security advice and financial support for some 30 relocations within Afghanistan. We have not found an intimidation case where the threat is such that we need to relocate the local staff to the UK to make them safe. This intimidation policy is open-ended, and applies to all local staff regardless of date or duration of service.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-09-10T16:09:12.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417232/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417232/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Afghanistan: Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many locally-employed Afghan interpreters who worked alongside the British Army have (a) applied for relocation to the UK and (b) been resettled in the UK under his Department's resettlement package to date.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","9114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417233","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-10","<p>There are no clean up costs to the Ministry of Defence (MOD) as land is sold as seen. If contamination of MOD owned land is found this is reflected in the sale price.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-09-10T16:10:34.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417233/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417233/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Ministry of Defence: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the clean-up costs of land owned by his Department that (a) has been sold in the last year and (b) is earmarked for sale.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417234","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-10","<p>The valuation of commercial land owned by the Ministry of Defence cannot be released as to do so would prejudice commercial interests.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-09-10T16:11:24.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417234/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417234/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Ministry of Defence: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the value of commercial land owned by his Department that has been earmarked for sale.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417235","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-14","<p>The steps we are taking include targeted recruitment campaigns, changing the culture of the Service environment, providing opportunities for flexible employment, reviewing the ban on women serving in ground close combat roles and improving equality and diversity training.</p><p> </p><p>The Army are also reviewing all job specifications which state experience in a Front Line command post is an essential requirement and removing this if appropriate to do so.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-09-14T15:54:46.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417235/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417235/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Armed Forces: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to increase the number of women in high-ranking positions in the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417236","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-11","<p>All members of the Armed Forces receive an attractive package of terms and conditions of service which include a competitive salary with incremental pay scales, a non-contributory pension scheme, subsidised accommodation and access to free medical and dental care. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) also uses a variety of financial incentives to assist with recruitment and retention of Armed Forces personnel to tackle shortages in particular areas.</p><p> </p><p>The Services monitor outflow very carefully, although it should be recognised that some churn in strength, particularly in the lower ranks, is welcome and helps to refresh the Armed Forces. Instances of high outflow are mitigated through a variety of management actions which include extensions of Service, financial retention initiatives and inter-Service transfers.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD has long standing links with private sector companies, and we work closely with them to help resettle Service personnel at the end of their Service careers through programmes such as the Career Transition Partnership.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","9331","2015-09-11T13:42:56.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417236/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417236/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to retain personnel in the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417237","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-15","<p>Each Service has Harmony Guidelines for the amount of time any individual should spend away from their home unit (whether in battle zones or performing other duties) including time on deployment.</p><p> </p><p>A breach of Individual Harmony Guidelines occurs when Service personnel experience separated service for longer than the period outlined in Individual Harmony Guidelines. These are: for the Royal Navy/Royal Marines, no more than 660 days away over a 36 month period; for the Army, no more than 498 days away away over a 36 month period; and for the Royal Air Force, no more than 468 days away over a 36 month period. These guidelines are different for each Service reflecting the differing structures of, and differing roles and duties undertaken by, each Service.</p><p> </p><p>The latest figures on single Service levels of harmony breaches were released by the Department as an official statistic (as part of the Monthly Service Personnel Statistics publication) on 10 September 2015 and are linked below.</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/459461/Service_Personnel_Statistics-1-August-2015.pdf#page=10</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-09-15T15:01:40.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417237/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417237/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) average and (b) maximum period for duty in battle zones is for (i) army, (ii) Royal Navy and (iii) RAF personnel.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417238","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-15","<p>None.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-09-15T15:03:37.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417238/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417238/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Navy: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many ships cannot go to sea due to shortages in specialist personnel.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417239","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-09-11","<p>All members of the Armed Forces receive an attractive package of terms and conditions of service which include a competitive salary with incremental pay scales, a non-contributory pension scheme, subsidised accommodation and access to free medical and dental care. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) also uses a variety of financial incentives to assist with recruitment and retention of Armed Forces personnel to tackle shortages in particular areas.</p><p> </p><p>The Services monitor outflow very carefully, although it should be recognised that some churn in strength, particularly in the lower ranks, is welcome and helps to refresh the Armed Forces. Instances of high outflow are mitigated through a variety of management actions which include extensions of Service, financial retention initiatives and inter-Service transfers.</p><p> </p><p>The MOD has long standing links with private sector companies, and we work closely with them to help resettle Service personnel at the end of their Service careers through programmes such as the Career Transition Partnership.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","9307","2015-09-11T13:42:56.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417239/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417239/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-09-07","Armed Forces: Private Military and Security Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to prevent veteran service personnel leaving to join private sector companies.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","9331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417240","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is currently conducting a Spending Review across all its programmes. The Government does not offer a running commentary on the Spending Review.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-14T14:22:12.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417240/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417240/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Primary Education: Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans her Department has to continue the universal infant free school meals programme.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","9136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417241","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>To improve procurement efficiencies in the schools sector the Department for Education works closely with the Crown Commercial Service and other public sector buying organisations to create deals which better meet school needs. Schools procurement guidance is available on GOV.UK together with practical steps that schools can take such as, encouraging schools to share market intelligence, expertise, and buying common items collaboratively to achieve economies of scale from the supply market.</p><p> </p><p>The department works closely with representative school groups such as the Association of School and College Leaders and the National Association of School Business Managers to raise awareness of good deals available for schools and the benefits of adopting best practice procurement. To increase commercial capability and capacity in schools we have piloted a train the trainer programme which has been very well received.</p><p> </p><p>Schools procurement guidance is published online at:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/collections/departmental-advice-schools" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/collections/departmental-advice-schools</a></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-09-14T14:24:19.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417241/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417241/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Schools: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to improve procurement in the education sector; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417242","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>The table below sets out the number of schools funded by the local authority and centrally in West Sussex. There have been an increasing number of providers who are funded centrally as they join the academy programme. It should be noted that academies are funded using the same local authority formulae as a local authority maintained school, and any differences locally reflect the demographic profile and population volume of the school or academy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid centrally [1]</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid by the LA [2]</p></td><td><p>283</p></td><td><p>270</p></td><td><p>244</p></td><td><p>245</p></td><td><p>232</p></td><td><p>229</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>287</p></td><td><p>285</p></td><td><p>279</p></td><td><p>280</p></td><td><p>278</p></td><td><p>279</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures reflect the financial year April - March</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] Providers included in the academy programme:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Academy</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free Schools</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Studio Schools</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UTCs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>[2] Providers not in the academies programme:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Community School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Community Special School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Foundation School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Foundation Special School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Voluntary Aided School</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Voluntary Controlled School</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-14T14:35:20.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417242/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417242/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Schools: West Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many schools in the county of West Sussex were funded (a) by the local authority and (b) centrally in the financial years 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417243","Department for Education","false","2015-09-09","<p>The Department for Education publishes a list of all state-funded and independent schools in England on the GOV.UK website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-in-england</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The list includes the name and type of establishment (community, voluntary aided etc.) for schools located in the West Sussex local authority area.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-09-09T15:53:57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417243/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417243/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Schools: West Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the name is of each (a) community school, (b) voluntary aided school, (c) voluntary controlled school, (d) foundation school and (e) academy school in the county of West Sussex.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417244","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>Average per pupil revenue funding figures for West Sussex are given below. With the introduction of the dedicated schools grant (DSG) in 2006-07, the changes to the funding mechanism meant figures were no longer available to be shown split by phase of education.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for financial years 2005 to 2013 are shown below. These are in cash terms:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Average revenue per pupil funding (cash)</p></td><td><p>2005-06 (baseline)</p></td><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Sussex LA </strong></p></td><td><p>3,680</p></td><td><p>3,890</p></td><td><p>4,150</p></td><td><p>4,320</p></td><td><p>4,520</p></td><td><p>4,740</p></td><td><p>4,710</p></td><td><p>4,710</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These are in real terms using July 2015 GDP deflators in 2014-15 prices:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Average revenue per pupil funding (real)</p></td><td><p>2005-06 (baseline)</p></td><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Sussex LA </strong></p></td><td><p>4,500</p></td><td><p>4,630</p></td><td><p>4,800</p></td><td><p>4,880</p></td><td><p>4,970</p></td><td><p>5,080</p></td><td><p>4,950</p></td><td><p>4,870</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Per pupil figures are using DSG allocations plus other schools related grants, e.g. school standards grant, school standards grant (personalisation), standards fund, and pupils aged 3-15 rounded to the nearest £10. Most of the additional grants were mainstreamed into DSG in 2011-12.</p><p> </p><p>The changes to DSG funding in financial year 2013 to 2014 with funding allocated through three blocks, namely schools, early years and high needs, means there is no longer a comparable overall figure with previous years. The table below shows the DSG schools block unit funding figures in cash and real terms for West Sussex LA:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>DSG schools block per pupil funding</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p> </p><p>2015-2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Sussex LA (cash)</strong></p></td><td><p>4,196</p></td><td><p>4,196</p></td><td><p>4,198</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Sussex LA (real)*</strong></p></td><td><p>4,254</p></td><td><p>4,196</p></td><td><p>4,156</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*Real terms figures shown in 2014-15 prices using GDP deflators at 08.07.15</p><p> </p><p>Since 2011-12 schools have received the Pupil Premium which targets funding at pupils from the most deprived backgrounds to help them achieve their full potential. In 2011-12, the Premium was allocated for each pupil known to be eligible for Free School Meals, looked after children and children of parents in the armed services. In 2012-13 coverage was expanded to include pupils known to have been eligible for Free School Meals at any point in the last six years. The amounts per pupil for each type of pupil are shown in the following table in cash terms:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Pupil Premium per pupil (£)</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>2015-2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free School Meal Pupil Primary</p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£953</p></td><td><p>£1323</p></td><td><p>£1320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free School Meal Pupil Secondary</p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td><td><p>£935</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Service Children</p></td><td><p>£200</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td><td><p>£300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Looked After Children</p></td><td><p>£488</p></td><td><p>£623</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£1900*</p></td><td><p>£1900*</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*Also includes children adopted from care</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Total Pupil Premium allocations for West Sussex local authority for each year are shown in the following table in cash terms:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Pupil Premium Allocations (£ millions)</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>2015-16 (prov.)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Sussex</p></td><td><p>4.263</p></td><td><p>9.502</p></td><td><p>15.393</p></td><td><p>21.033</p></td><td><p>21.339</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These figures in real terms:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Pupil Premium Allocations (£ millions)</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>2015-16 (prov.)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Sussex</p></td><td><p>4.483</p></td><td><p>9.833</p></td><td><p>15.607</p></td><td><p>21.033</p></td><td><p>21.128</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Price Base: Real terms at 2014-15 prices, based on GDP deflators as at 08.07.2015</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below shows capital funding for the financial years that are available. The data is in cash terms as allocations are phased across more than one year making real terms calculations meaningless. Complete information on the split of capital between phases of education is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><table><thead><tr><td><p>West Sussex</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>Capital allocations</p></td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>44.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-07</p></td><td><p>36.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>55.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>50.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>77.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>94.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>121.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>45.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>38.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>54.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16 (prov.)</p></td><td><p>18.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>1. Capital allocations includes capital grant and supported borrowing allocations.</p><p> </p><p>2. Figures are rounded to the nearest £100,000.</p><p> </p><p>3. Funding in 2015-16 is still subject to project progress and is therefore subject to change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-14T14:32:33.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417244/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417244/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much (a) revenue and (b) capital funding has been provided to each pupil in state (i) primary and (ii) secondary schools in the county of West Sussex (A) in cash terms and (B) at 2015 prices in each financial year since 2005-06.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417245","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>In response to PQs 9189-9193, please find attached an Excel workbook that details the individual school and academy budgets and pupil numbers for all providers in the West Sussex local authority area. These have been sourced wherever possible up to 2012-2013 from published section 251 statements, which detail local authority spending at school level and from published school and academy allocations for 2013-14 and 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2005-06 there has been an increasing number of providers who are funded centrally as they join the academy programme. It should be noted that academies are funded using the same local authority formulae as an LA maintained school, and any differences locally reflect the demographic profile and population of the school or academy.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","9189 ; 9190 ; 9192 ; 9193","2015-09-14T15:53:33.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417245/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417245/answer","9189-9193 Attachment 100915.xlsx","Budget and pupil number data","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417245/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Voluntary Schools: West Sussex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the (a) budget and (b) pupil number was for each voluntary controlled school in the county of West Sussex in each year from 2005-06 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417246","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is committed to making school funding fairer, to protecting the schools budget and to maintaining the Minimum Funding Levels uplift in this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has already made significant progress on these commitments. We have protected schools funding for 2016-17 and baked into the baseline the extra £390 million we allocated in the previous parliament to the least fairly funded local authorities. We will come forward with our proposals on making school funding fairer in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State and I met with my Honourable Friend the Member for Mid Sussex and colleagues from West Sussex recently to discuss the issue. The Government fully understands the strength of feeling among Members that school funding needs to be made fairer.</p><p />","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-14T14:40:49.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417246/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/417246/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-07","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to alter the school funding formula; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","9187"
