and Social Care Information Centre</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><p>1. Data is received at practice level, however the practice data cannot be used to estimate prevalence for small areas as practices serve registered patients, not defined geographical areas. The QOF data has been provided down to CCG/PCT level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2. The figures provided are a snapshot ‘as at 31 March each year’ and are for people of all ages, as a breakdown by age group and gender is not available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>3. The objective of the QOF is to improve the quality of care that patients are given by rewarding practices for the quality of care they provide to their patients. QOF is therefore an incentive payment scheme. Participation by practices is entirely voluntary, though participation rates are over 95%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>4. As QOF registers are constructed to underpin indicators on quality of care, they do not necessarily equate to prevalence as may be defined by epidemiologists. For example, prevalence figures based on QOF registers may differ from prevalence from other sources because of coding and definitional issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>5. The number of patients on clinical registers can be used to calculate disease prevalence, expressing the number of patients on each register as a percentage of the number of patients on practices’ lists. Therefore, ‘raw prevalence’ for a clinical area is defined as:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Raw Prevalence = (number on clinical register / number on practice list) *100</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","8755","2015-09-09T16:18:50.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416289/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416289/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416289/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-04","Dementia: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the rate of dementia among each (a) age group and (b) gender in (i) Allerdale borough and (ii) Copeland borough has been in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","8771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416290","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We are committed to ensuring benefits are processed as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Over the last three years we have seen a marked improvement. The improvement in the experience of our customers was shared in the recently published Annual Report and Accounts, 2014-15 here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are unable to provide data specifically for Nottingham North constituency.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-11T13:27:08.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416290/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416290/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to speed up the processing of benefit claims; what effect such measures are having on processing times in (a) the UK on (b) the smallest area that can be distinguished which includes Nottingham North constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","9028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416291","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions cannot provide a figure on ‘how many clinical trials have been advertised through Jobcentre Plus as employment opportunities’ because vacancies such as this are not accepted on Universal Jobmatch as they breach the Terms &amp; Conditions, therefore no statistical information is held.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Jobmatch is the main conduit by which job vacancies are advertised by Jobcentre Plus, however there will be instances where vacancies are advertised locally in Jobcentre Plus offices outside of Universal Jobmatch. The Department for Work &amp; Pension’s policy around clinical trial vacancies on Universal Jobmatch is; any vacancies that are advertised as clinical trials on Universal Jobmatch would not be accepted as they breach the Terms &amp; Conditions. Where a clinical trial vacancy is identified on Universal Jobmatch the vacancy will immediately be removed and the employer contacted to advise that they have breached the Terms &amp; Conditions and that any subsequent breaches could result in their account being suspended.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","9051","2015-09-09T13:58:43.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416291/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416291/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Vacancies: Clinical Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many clinical trials have been advertised to jobseekers through Jobcentre Plus as employment opportunities.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416292","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions cannot provide a figure on ‘how many clinical trials have been advertised through Jobcentre Plus as employment opportunities’ because vacancies such as this are not accepted on Universal Jobmatch as they breach the Terms &amp; Conditions, therefore no statistical information is held.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Jobmatch is the main conduit by which job vacancies are advertised by Jobcentre Plus, however there will be instances where vacancies are advertised locally in Jobcentre Plus offices outside of Universal Jobmatch. The Department for Work &amp; Pension’s policy around clinical trial vacancies on Universal Jobmatch is; any vacancies that are advertised as clinical trials on Universal Jobmatch would not be accepted as they breach the Terms &amp; Conditions. Where a clinical trial vacancy is identified on Universal Jobmatch the vacancy will immediately be removed and the employer contacted to advise that they have breached the Terms &amp; Conditions and that any subsequent breaches could result in their account being suspended.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","9050","2015-09-09T13:58:43.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416292/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416292/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Vacancies: Clinical Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his policy is on the advertising of clinical trials to jobseekers as employment opportunities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416293","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-09","<p>The Government has ensured access to the Postcode Address File (PAF) through primary legislation. The Postal Services Act 2000 (as amended by the Postal Services Act 2011) specifies that the PAF must be made available to anyone who wishes to use it on reasonable terms.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This legislative protection will continue to apply regardless of Royal Mail's ownership.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the effect of the inclusion of the Postcode Address File in the sale of Royal Mail on either small businesses or other users.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-09-09T15:34:49.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416293/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416293/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416293/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Post Codes: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the inclusion of the Postcode Address File in the sale of Royal Mail on (a) small businesses and (b) other users of formerly public postcode data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","9052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416294","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) published the Provisional Findings from their investigation into the energy markets in July alongside a notice of possible remedies to address the issues identified; their final report setting out their final remedies is not expected until December 2015. This Government remains committed to implementing the recommendations the CMA will set out in their Final Report.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-11T13:43:11.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416294/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416294/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, for what reasons she is not implementing the recommendation of the Competition and Markets Authority that Ofgem should be the single provider of a switching and comparison website for energy.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416295","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department routinely considers examples from other advanced economies in order to inform its policies. As part of the investigation into the energy markets, the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) has also identified different forms switching and comparison sites for energy can take in other advanced economies and is considering alternatives as part of their possible remedies. This Government is committed to implementing the recommendations the CMA will set out in their Final Report, expected in December 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-11T13:44:06.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416295/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416295/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department has conducted research on one-stop-shop switching and comparison sites for energy in other advanced economies in order to inform its policies.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416296","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>Attracting private sector owners in to the Green Investment Bank (GIB) will enable the company to grow its business, giving the GIB access to a much greater volume of capital than would be the case if GIB were to remain in 100% Government ownership, including allowing it to borrow.</p><p>This will enable the company to have the greatest possible impact and should lead to more green projects getting financed more quickly than would otherwise be the case.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-09-14T13:29:36.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416296/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416296/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the sale of the Government's majority stake in the Green Investment Bank on the level of investments made by that bank.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416297","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-18","<p>The Government strongly supports reform to strengthen the EU Emissions Trading System (ETS). Ministers and officials have discussed EU ETS reform recently with counterparts in other Member States, as well as the European Commission and industry representatives. My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State will continue these discussions at the forthcoming Green Growth Summit in Brussels, which will be attended by a range of European public and private organisations.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-18T13:26:01.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416297/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416297/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","EU Emissions Trading Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent discussions she has had with her EU counterparts on strengthening the EU Emissions Trading Scheme.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416298","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>The EU has an effective carbon market in the form of the EU Emissions Trading System (EU ETS), though an oversupply of allowances in the system means it is not delivering the degree of low carbon investment it should. The Government worked hard with European partners to secure agreement to the EU ETS Market Stability Reserve to address this, and welcomes the Commission’s recent proposals for further reform of EU ETS from 2021.</p><p>While a single global carbon market is unrealistic in the foreseeable future, over forty countries and sub-national jurisdictions, covering around 12% of global emissions, are implementing carbon pricing policies. The Government is supporting linking between these bottom-up initiatives by developing an international framework through the UNFCCC, through political engagement, for example the G7, and International Climate Fund projects. Over time these linked schemes should converge towards a single global market.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-14T16:41:14.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416298/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416298/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she expects a fully functioning carbon market to be operational.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416299","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-15","<p>The Government and the regulator, Ofgem, are actively exploring the operation of the distributed energy supply landscape, including the potential costs and benefits for consumers and the implications for regulatory arrangements. Ofgem are due to publish their response to the discussion paper on Non-Traditional Business Models in the Autumn which looks at different models for the supply of energy. DECC officials will work closely with Ofgem over the coming months to understand the implications for the Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-15T17:09:05.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416299/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416299/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Electricity: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to make it easier for retail electricity consumers to negotiate distributed energy contracts with energy companies.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416300","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is committed to keeping energy bills as low as possible as part of a long-term, coherent and affordable policy framework. As part of this we will continue to improve targeting of support to those most in need.</p><p>The Government already has a number of policies in place to ensure that energy and climate change policies help those that need it most. In particular, the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) specifically supports low income households and those at risk of fuel poverty with measures to improve the energy efficiency of their homes. This generates a net financial benefit over the long term, and also helps ensure that energy bills are lower than they would otherwise have been. ECO is estimated to support around 260,000 households on low incomes or in low income areas each year to March 2017.</p><p>Furthermore, the Warm Home Discount (WHD) generates the dual benefits of supporting over 2 million low income households each year with a £140 discount on their energy costs, and acting as a redistributive mechanism to help those least able to pay.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>-</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-14T14:27:54.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416300/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416300/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Energy: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to ensure that the effect of existing green and social levies is more progressively distributed across the income scale.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416301","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-10","<p>Following DECC research into the optimal display of consumption comparisons for domestic consumers, Energy UK agreed to take forward work on a consumption comparison webtool, as part of a voluntary agreement between Government and energy suppliers. This enables consumers to input their own details and see how their consumption compares to similar households and is available online at: <a href="http://www.comparemyenergy.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.comparemyenergy.org.uk/</a></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-10T14:13:35.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416301/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416301/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Energy: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will make it her policy to require the provision to energy consumers of a breakdown of their energy consumption compared with similarly sized households or businesses.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416302","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-09","<p>Fuel poverty is measured at a household rather than an individual level.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Low Income High Costs (LIHC) indicator is used to measure fuel poverty in England, following recommendations from Professor Hills’ independent review of fuel poverty.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Sub-regional fuel poverty levels are modelled using a combination of national data taken from the English Housing Survey and nationally available small area datasets such as the census. The 2013 sub-regional figures, and the full methodology behind them, can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fuel-poverty-sub-regional-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fuel-poverty-sub-regional-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the number and proportion of households that are fuel poor under the Low Income High Costs indicator in the Greenwich and Woolwich constituency since 2011 (the first year to record sub-regional fuel poverty under the LIHC indicator).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong><em>Year</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Estimated number of </em></strong></p><p><strong><em>households</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Estimated number of </em></strong></p><p><strong><em>fuel poor households</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Proportion of </em></strong></p><p><strong><em>fuel poor households (%)</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013*</strong></p></td><td><p>47,280</p></td><td><p>4,125</p></td><td><p>8.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>44,143</p></td><td><p>3,442</p></td><td><p>7.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>43,482</p></td><td><p>2,976</p></td><td><p>6.8</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>*Note: 2013 estimates use an updated energy consumption model</em></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Prior to the LIHC indicator, the 10 per cent measure of fuel poverty was used – under this measure, households are deemed to be in fuel poverty if they need to spend more than 10 per cent of their income on fuel in order to achieve an adequate level of warmth.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In 2010, the number of households estimated to be in fuel poverty in the Greenwich and Woolwich constituency under the 10 per cent measure was 4,525, around 10.6% of all households. Estimates prior to 2010 are available from the <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130109092117/http:/decc.gov.uk/en/content/cms/statistics/fuelpov_stats/archive/archive.aspx" target="_blank">fuel poverty statistics archive</a> page.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are fully committed to tackling fuel poverty in England and to meeting our fuel poverty targets. A successful approach to keeping homes warmer for less needs to be long-term, stable, coherent, and affordable, and targeted at those who need it most. The fuel poverty strategy published in March 2015 sets out a clear policy of working towards improving energy efficiency standards in the homes of the fuel poor. Alongside Winter Fuel Payments and Cold Weather Payments, millions of low income and vulnerable households receive support through the Warm Home Discount and Energy Company Obligation which support installation of heating and insulation measures as well as direct reductions in consumers’ energy bills.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-09T15:41:30.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416302/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416302/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Fuel Poverty: Greenwich and Woolwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the number of people in Greenwich and Woolwich constituency affected by fuel poverty in each year since 2007.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416303","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-11","<p>DECC has not estimated investment in renewable energy by constituency. However, as at the end of June 2015, 596 kW of solar photovoltaic capacity had been installed in Greenwich and Woolwich under the feed-in tariff scheme (see: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sub-regional-feed-in-tariffs-confirmed-on-the-cfr-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sub-regional-feed-in-tariffs-confirmed-on-the-cfr-statistics</a>).</p><p>DECC also reports on heat accreditations at local authority level (see <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rhi-deployment-data-july-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/rhi-deployment-data-july-2015</a> , tables 1.6 and 2.11), as well as publishing a breakdown of renewable electricity generation and deployment by region (at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/regional-renewable-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/regional-renewable-statistics</a>).</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-11T13:42:33.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416303/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416303/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Renewable Energy: Greenwich and Woolwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the level of Government investment in renewable energy in Greenwich and Woolwich constituency since 2010.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416304","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-15","<p>The coalition Government introduced an Emissions Performance Standard for all new fossil power stations as part of the Energy Act 2013 when the case for extending the scope of the EPS to include existing plant was considered by Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-15T17:08:44.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416304/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416304/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Power Stations: Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will introduce an emissions performance standard applied to all UK power stations.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416305","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-16","<p>We expect the role of unabated coal in the UK’s electricity mix to decline as a result of deployment of low carbon alternatives, the cost of generation and the investment needed to meet new pollution abatement standards. The Department’s analysis (central scenario) shows that unabated coal is expected to account for around 1% of total UK generation by 2025.</p><p>The Government’s planning policy prevents the building of new coal power plants without carbon capture and storage.</p><p><em>Source: DECC Updated energy and emissions projections 2014 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/368021/Updated_energy_and_emissions_projections2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/368021/Updated_energy_and_emissions_projections2014.pdf</a></em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-16T13:11:11.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416305/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416305/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Coal Fired Power Stations: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to ensure that all UK coal fire power stations will be offline by 2027.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416306","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-11","<p>We have taken steps to increase competition in domestic retail market and there are now 31 suppliers providing choice to consumers, up from 13 in 2010. The Department has also supported work to make the market more transparent. We provided legislative backing to Ofgem’s retail market reforms to make the market simpler, clearer, and fairer, and have committed to implementing the recommendation formal remedies to be set out in the Final Report of the Competition and Market Authority’s investigation into the energy market.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-11T09:06:48.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416306/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416306/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to make the retail energy market more transparent and facilitate greater consumer choice.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","8561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416307","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department has not made an assessment of the interaction between VAT thresholds and the minimum wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Businesses are only required to register for VAT when the total value of their taxable supplies of goods and services in the preceding 12 months exceeds the current VAT registration threshold, which was increased to £82,000 with effect from 1 April 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","8839 ; 8886","2015-09-14T15:04:43.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416307/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416307/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Small Businesses: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the increase of the minimum wage on small businesses which as a result of that increase will begin to operate above the VAT threshold.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416308","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department has not made an assessment of the interaction between VAT thresholds and the minimum wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Businesses are only required to register for VAT when the total value of their taxable supplies of goods and services in the preceding 12 months exceeds the current VAT registration threshold, which was increased to £82,000 with effect from 1 April 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","8838 ; 8886","2015-09-14T15:04:43.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416308/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416308/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Small Businesses: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of the number of small businesses that will begin to operate over the VAT threshold as a result of complying with the new minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416309","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>This Department has regular and frequent discussions with businesses of all sizes and across all sectors on a wide range of issues including the National Minimum Wage (NMW). In addition, the Low Pay Commission (LPC) will continue to play a key role in recommending the NMW and National Living Wage (NLW) rates going forward. In their report to Government the LPC consults widely and considers and reflects the views and representations from a wide range of businesses and sectors of the economy.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","8856","2015-09-14T16:04:37.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416309/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416309/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Small Businesses: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations have been made to his Department on the effect of the increase in the minimum wage on small businesses.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416310","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department has not made an assessment of the interaction between VAT thresholds and the minimum wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Businesses are only required to register for VAT when the total value of their taxable supplies of goods and services in the preceding 12 months exceeds the current VAT registration threshold, which was increased to £82,000 with effect from 1 April 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","8838 ; 8839","2015-09-14T15:04:43.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416310/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416310/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Small Businesses: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the increase in the minimum wage on small businesses operating under the VAT threshold.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416311","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government has chosen to maintain the highest VAT registration threshold in the EU (set at £82,000 from 1 April 2015). The Government may not increase this threshold further, aside from maintaining its value in line with inflation, without the consent of the European Commission and the unanimous agreement of all EU Member States.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-09-14T14:49:26.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416311/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416311/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-04","Small Businesses: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of increasing the VAT threshold so that small businesses complying with the new national minimum wage can continue to operate below the VAT threshold.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416312","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>This Department has regular and frequent discussions with businesses of all sizes and across all sectors on a wide range of issues including the National Minimum Wage (NMW). In addition, the Low Pay Commission (LPC) will continue to play a key role in recommending the NMW and National Living Wage (NLW) rates going forward. In their report to Government the LPC consults widely and considers and reflects the views and representations from a wide range of businesses and sectors of the economy.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","8840","2015-09-14T16:04:37.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416312/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416312/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Minimum Wage: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations have been made to his Department on the effect of the increase in minimum wage on small businesses.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","8856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416313","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>All healthcare professionals (HCPs) who carry out either Work Capability Assessments or Personal Independence Payment assessments undergo thorough training in disability analysis, as well as training in specific conditions, including mental health conditions.</p><p> </p><p>Mental Health Champions are available to provide advice and support to HCPs on health conditions and disabilities affecting mental, cognitive, intellectual and behavioural function.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-09T14:07:51.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416313/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416313/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what specialist training is given to employment and support allowance and personal independence payment assessors on handling claimants with mental health issues.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416314","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>The information is not available. Work Clubs are taken forward at the discretion of Jobcentre Plus District Managers.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-09T14:45:25.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416314/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416314/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Jobclubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants have (a) participated in and (b) found work through Work Clubs in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416315","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>Official statistics record starts to sector-based work academy pre-employment training only. The Department does not collate information on outcomes, nor the number of benefit claimants finding work through a sector-based work academy placement.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-09T14:34:15.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416315/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416315/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Employment Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants have found work through a placement with a sector-based work academy in each year since such schemes have been available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416316","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p>Once a decision has been made to award a claim, payment is activated. If there are no checks triggered payment is automatically activated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The majority of new claimants to Personal Independence Payment will be paid any arrears of benefit within a few days of the decision being made.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-09T14:27:44.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416316/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416316/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance is issued by his Department on how long successful claimants of personal independence payment should wait before their first payment arrives once a decision has been made to award the claim.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416317","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>Part (a) Tax Credits</p><p> </p><p>Number of new Tax Credit claims received for the period April 2014 to end July 2015 is included in the list below:</p><p> </p><p>Claims received 12/13 - 1,072,007</p><p>Claims received 13/14 - 1,019,719</p><p>Claims received 14/15 - 922,661</p><p>Claims received April 15 to end July 15 - 320,673</p><p> </p><p>Part (b) Jobseekers Allowance; Part (c) Employment and Support Allowance and Part (d) Income Support</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The information requested for Part (b) Jobseekers Allowance, Part (c) Employment and Support Allowance and Part (d) Income Support is not available in the Public Domain.</p><p> </p><p>Part (e) Housing Benefit</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of claims for Part (e) Housing Benefit is published and available at:-</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/housing-benefit-statistics-on-speed-of-processing-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/housing-benefit-statistics-on-speed-of-processing-2014-to-2015</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-09T13:46:14.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416317/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416317/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many new claims for (a) tax credits, (b) jobseeker's allowance, (c) employment and support allowance, (d) income support and (e) housing benefit have been made since April 2014.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416318","Department of Health","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Since 2013-14, the Department has been collecting data on the amount invoiced by National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts, together with amounts recovered and written off by those organisations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The data is not broken down in any detail, and as such it is impossible to classify by patients’ countries of origin, nationality or immigration status. As such, it will include data on United Kingdom nationals no longer ordinarily resident in the UK and who have been charged under Regulations as well as data pertaining to non-UK nationals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This data does not provide the amount of debt owed to NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts by non-UK patients receiving NHS hospital treatment.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","8408","2015-09-14T14:54:44.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416318/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416318/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-04","Health Services: Illegal Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many illegal immigrants have received free treatment in NHS hospitals in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416319","Department of Health","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Since 2013-14, the Department has been collecting data on the amount invoiced by National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts, together with amounts recovered and written off by those organisations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The data is not broken down in any detail, and as such it is impossible to classify by patients’ countries of origin, nationality or immigration status. As such, it will include data on United Kingdom nationals no longer ordinarily resident in the UK and who have been charged under Regulations as well as data pertaining to non-UK nationals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This data does not provide the amount of debt owed to NHS trusts and NHS foundation trusts by non-UK patients receiving NHS hospital treatment.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","8407","2015-09-14T14:54:44.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416319/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416319/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-04","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much owed to the NHS by non-UK patients receiving treatment remains outstanding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416320","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>We do not keep records of this type of information.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-11T13:03:40.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416320/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416320/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Managers: Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people declaring themselves as a Company Director have applied for universal credit to date; whether their household income was considered before a decision was made on their application; and what proportion of such claims have been successful.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416321","Department for Education","false","2015-09-14","<p>We will continue to ensure that children from the poorest families benefit from a free school meal. The introduction of Universal Credit and simplification of the benefits system mean that the eligibility criteria for free school meals will need to be updated. The Department for Education is continuing to work closely with the Department for Work and Pensions on this. In the meantime, any child in a family in receipt of Universal Credit will continue to be entitled to free school meals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-09-14T14:06:08.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416321/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416321/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-09-04","Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, by what date she expects to confirm whether children of parents who claim universal credit while in employment will be entitled to free school meals.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416322","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Government is currently consulting on a proposal to increase certain court fees for civil proceedings in magistrates’ courts by 10% and has published an impact assessment alongside the consultation paper. A scheme of fee waivers or remissions exists to protect access to justice for those who cannot afford the pay the fee.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-09-14T14:08:10.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416322/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416322/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-09-04","Civil Proceedings: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effect of changes in the cost of bringing a case to magistrates' courts on low income households' access to justice.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416323","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-14","<p /> <p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-14T11:03:56.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416323/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416323/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","New Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many start-ups initiated by benefits claimants on the Work For Yourself programme were sustained beyond (a) six and (b) 12 months.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416324","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>The information as requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The information that is available, on the number of adverse Jobseeker's Allowance sanction decisions made in each year since 2010, is published and available at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>:</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-11T13:00:23.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416324/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416324/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Jobseeker's Allowance: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many suspensions have been applied to jobseeker's allowance claims in each year since 2010; and how many such suspensions have resulted in the immediate withdrawal of benefit payments.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416325","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-09-14","<p>Affordable rents were never defined as 70% of the local market rent. Affordable Rents were introduced in 2010, and with rents to be set at any level, up to 80 per cent, of market rents. Rent setting has to take into consideration local needs and the local market context. In London the average Affordable Rent is around 65 per cent of market rents.</p><p> </p><p>The Affordable Rent model allows us to reduce the level of grant required for each home from over £66,000 to an average of £24,500 per home. This enables us to deliver more homes for every pound of Government investment, so more people in housing need can have access to a good quality home with at a sub-market rent. Since April 2010, we have delivered 260,000 new affordable homes.</p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office report on the <em>Financial viability of the social housing sector</em> concluded that the Affordable Rent model maximised benefits and the number of homes that could be delivered within the available grant funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-09-14T13:59:54.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416325/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416325/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-09-04","Housing Starts: Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the increase in affordable home starts between 2009-10 and 2013-14 was attributable to changing the definition of affordable from 70 to 80 per cent of local private rents.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","9037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416326","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-09","<p>Where a parking contravention has occurred in respect of a designated disabled parking space, local authorities that have taken on civil enforcement powers may issue a penalty charge under powers contained in the Traffic Management Act 2004. In areas still subject to police enforcement, traffic wardens may issue fixed penalties.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>If the contravention involves the misuse of a ‘Blue Badge’, which is a criminal offence, either a local authority or the police may prosecute the offender under section 117 of the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-09T15:25:31.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416326/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416326/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-04","Parking: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers (a) local authorities and (b) the police have to enforce proper use of designated disabled parking spaces on public highways.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","8762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416327","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>Jobcentre Plus local offices can already use the Flexible Support Fund for DBS checks if they think this is appropriate on a case by case basis.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-09-09T15:16:42.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416327/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416327/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Vetting: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his Department's policy to fund Standard disclosure and barring checks (DBS) for jobseekers' allowance claimants who have received a job offer conditional on obtaining a DBS certificate.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","8763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416328","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>I am interpreting this question as asking for the definition of people who are helped by Access to Work.</p><p> </p><p>The following definition of the number of people helped in a given year is provided in the published statistics: &quot;individuals who have been assessed within the year or for whom there is an [Access to Work] element where approval has been made (including nil cost) and the element has been made available within the year.&quot;</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-11T12:41:24.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416328/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416328/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria his Department applies to identify those people in receipt of Access to Work support.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","8463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416329","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-11","<p /> <p>The £40,800 per year limit to individual Access to Work grants will be applied to new applicants from October 1st 2015. Individuals with current Access to Work grants will not be subject to the limit until April 2018.</p><p> </p><p>There will be no difference in criteria applied to customers affected by limit compared with those who are not.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-11T13:21:46.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416329/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416329/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria his Department has set for claimants of Access to Work support to qualify for the maximum level of support.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","8461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416330","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-11","<p>Our aid relationship with any government is based on an assessment of their commitment to our Partnership Principles, which include human rights.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government of Pakistan has publically recognised the problems facing minorities, and the need to bring an end to religious persecution. We remain fully committed to working in partnership with them to achieve this.<br></p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2015-09-11T13:29:46.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416330/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416330/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-04","Pakistan: Minority Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to make aid to Pakistan contingent on that country making progress on protecting religious and social minorities.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","8462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416331","Home Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>The additional checks introduced as a result of the findings of the report of the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration are as follows:</p><p>• Financial checks</p><p>• Further verification of referee details</p><p>• Relevant information held by other government departments</p><p>• Full review of an applicant’s immigration compliance since arrival in the UK</p><p>Additional checks are carried out on cases assessed as having a medium or high likelihood of failing to satisfy the good character requirement, and the checks conducted depend on the specific circumstances of an individual case and any further investigation deemed necessary when the results of checks are received. No information is aggregated in national reporting systems to enable reporting on the time additional checks have added to the time taken to consider cases.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-09-10T14:06:52.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416331/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416331/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-04","British Nationality: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the report of the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration, published on 11 December 2014, what additional checks on British citizenship applications have been introduced as a result of the findings of that report; and how much time those checks have added to the time taken to consider cases.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","8777"
