"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416353","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-09","<p>Since the closure, Kids Company have transferred 1842 cases to local authorities for them to review and determine the support services required. Kids Company also supported children through their schools programme, which is in the process of being handed over to school staff. Funding is being made available to local authorities to support the transition of Kids Company children to other services.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","8708 ; 8709","2015-09-09T16:34:37.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416353/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416353/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-04","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government plans to provide funding to local authorities to help manage the effects of Kids Company's closure.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","8710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416354","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-09","<p>Upon taking responsibility for Youth Policy, the Cabinet Office commissioned an independent review of financial and governance controls at Kids Company in early 2014. This is published on gov.uk. Since the completion of this review, officials held regular discussions with Kids Company to monitor progress. Specific concerns raised by officials are set out in the request for a ministerial direction letter, also published on gov.uk</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","8833 ; 8957","2015-09-09T16:35:43.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416354/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416354/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-04","Kids Company: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what concerns his Department had about the leadership, management and governance at Kids Company when making its recent decisions on funding.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","8711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416355","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-09","<p>Upon taking responsibility for Youth Policy, the Cabinet Office commissioned an independent review of financial and governance controls at Kids Company in early 2014. This is published on gov.uk. Since the completion of this review, officials held regular discussions with Kids Company to monitor progress. Specific concerns raised by officials are set out in the request for a ministerial direction letter, also published on gov.uk</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","8711 ; 8833","2015-09-09T16:35:43.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416355/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416355/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-04","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when Cabinet Office officials first became aware of issues concerning leadership, management and governance at Kids Company.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","8957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416356","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>An independent review of financial and governance controls at Kids Company in early 2014 (published on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>) stated that ‘the main financial risk to the organisation is cashflow’ and that ‘without improving the cash position of the charity, it is not possible to build reserves and invest in new activities and locations’. Subsequent funding agreements between Cabinet Office and Kids Company included clear conditions that this position be improved.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","8932","2015-09-10T15:26:15.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416356/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416356/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416356/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-04","Kids Company: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the letter from the Permanent Secretary of the Cabinet Office to Cabinet Office Ministers dated 26 June 2015, published 16 July 2015, what conditions were attached to the grant made to Kids Company in April 2015 to encourage that charity to move to a more financially sustainable model; which aspects of that charity's business model the Government considered should become more financial sustainable; and for how long the Government had concerns about this matter.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","8931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416357","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>An independent review of financial and governance controls at Kids Company in early 2014 (published on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>) stated that ‘the main financial risk to the organisation is cashflow’ and that ‘without improving the cash position of the charity, it is not possible to build reserves and invest in new activities and locations’. Subsequent funding agreements between Cabinet Office and Kids Company included clear conditions that this position be improved.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","8931","2015-09-10T15:26:15.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416357/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416357/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416357/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-04","Kids Company: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the letter from the Permanent Secretary of the Cabinet Office to Cabinet Office Ministers dated 26 June 2015, published 16 July 2015, for what reasons his Department had limited confidence that Kids Company could implement changes set out in that charity's restructuring plans.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","8932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416358","Cabinet Office","false","2015-09-10","<p>The conditions of the latest grant agreements were intended to encourage Kids Company to move to a more financially sustainable model.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-09-10T15:29:48.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416358/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416358/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416358/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-09-04","Kids Company: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons his Department required the Chief Executive of Kids Company to step down before allocating further funding to that charity.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","8933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416359","Home Office","false","2015-09-08","<p>The Home Office has issued no guidance to the police on carrying throw ropes in police vehicles.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-09-08T16:59:57.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416359/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416359/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416359/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-09-04","Police: Throw Ropes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department has published for police services on carrying throw ropes in police vehicles.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","8617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416360","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-09-11","<p>If a party to the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPoA) thinks there has been a violation of the JCPoA they should notify the Joint Commission. The Joint Commission will discuss these concerns with a view to resolving them within 15 days. If the Joint Commission cannot resolve the matter, it will be considered by an Advisory Panel made up of the complainant, defendant and an independent party, and may also be considered in parallel by Foreign Ministers. If the concern still cannot be resolved and the complainant believes that the violation constitutes significant non-performance of JCPoA commitments then the matter will be escalated to the UN Security Council, which will vote on a resolution to continue the lifting of sanctions. If the Security Council does not adopt this resolution within 30 days, nuclear-related UN sanctions will automatically ‘snapback’. In addition to UN sanctions, the US and the EU can re-impose sanctions if Iran is in breach of its commitments.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-09-11T13:14:07.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416360/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416360/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416360/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-09-04","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what processes will initiate snap break of sanctions on Iran if a breach of the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action takes place.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","9048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416361","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport allocated funding of just under £4 million to Stoke on Trent City Council for local highways maintenance in the last financial year, 2014/15. This includes £1.3 million per annum towards a 25 year street lighting PFI project that commenced in 2003/04.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are also able to use revenue funding, allocated by the Department of Communities and Local Government through the Revenue Support Grant for maintaining their local highways.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Neither revenue nor capital highways maintenance block funding is ring-fenced and it is for local highway authorities, such as Stoke on Trent City Council, to decide upon their spending priorities across the whole range of services that they provide.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-11T13:19:41.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416361/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416361/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416361/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-04","Roads: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much was spent on road maintenance in Stoke-on-Trent local authority area in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","8486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416362","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-14","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-09-14T14:45:25.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416362/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416362/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-09-04","Working Tax Credit: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many public sector employees are currently in receipt of working tax credits.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","8487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416363","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department does not hold data on VED receipts directly attributed to local authority areas.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-09-11T13:22:45.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416363/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416363/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-09-04","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much vehicle excise duty was collected in Stoke-on-Trent local authority area in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","8499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416364","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-14","<p /> <p>Over 5.43 million workers have now been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension by their employer, many for the first time. This has reversed the downwards trend seen in workplace pension participation rates since 2003.</p><p> </p><p>So far opt out has been around 10 per cent, which is significantly lower than the original DWP estimate of around 30 per cent. This has seen the programme opt out assumption being adjusted to 15 per cent overall for the lifetime of the programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Automatic Enrolment will give around 10 million people the opportunity to save into a workplace pension - we expect to see 8 to 9 million people newly saving or saving more, generating £11 billion a year more in workplace pension saving by 2020.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-09-14T11:35:08.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416364/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416364/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-09-04","Occupational Pensions: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of auto-enrolment on private sector pension saving.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","8900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416365","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-14","<p>Defra recognises the importance of pollinators, including bees, and their value to food security and sustaining the natural environment. This is why Defra published the National Pollinator Strategy in November 2014:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-pollinator-strategy-for-bees-and-other-pollinators-in-england" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-pollinator-strategy-for-bees-and-other-pollinators-in-england</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Strategy is a ten-year plan to bring about the best possible conditions for pollinators to flourish across all land types. It identifies specific policy and evidence actions for government and others, and actions that everyone can take to help expand food, shelter and nest sites. The Strategy also seeks to address key gaps in our understanding about the status of pollinators.</p><p>To raise public awareness a ‘Call to Action’, “Bees’ Needs: Food and a Home” (<a href="http://www.beesneeds.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.beesneeds.org.uk</a>) was launched in July 2014. This is a simple message on the essential needs of pollinators and how to fulfil them.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-09-14T10:24:44.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416365/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416365/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-04","Pollinators","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support bees and pollinators.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","9045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416366","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-09-14","<p>The Department did not discuss this report, or its timing, with Cuadrilla. This was a draft internal paper and is not analytically robust. It refers to data from overseas studies which cannot be used to predict impacts in the UK with any degree of reliability. The UK has a robust regulatory regime that will ensure that the exploration and production of shale gas can be carried out in a safe and environmentally sound manner. We are committed to ensuring that communities feel the benefits of fracking. Investment in shale could reach £33 billion and support 64,000 jobs in the oil, gas, construction, engineering and chemical sectors. That would be good news for the whole of the UK economy.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-09-14T16:40:51.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416366/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416366/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-09-04","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department discussed (a) the Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs report, Shale Gas: Rural Economy Impacts, published in redacted form in March 2014 and (b) the timing of that report's release, in either redacted or full form, with Cuadrilla.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","9077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416367","Prime Minister","false","2015-09-11","<p>This was a draft internal DEFRA paper which was not analytically robust.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has a regulatory regime that will ensure that the exploration and production of shale gas can be carried out in a safe and environmentally sound manner. We are committed to ensuring that communities feel the benefits of fracking. Investment in shale could reach £33 billion and support 64,000 jobs in the oil, gas, construction, engineering and chemical sectors. That would be good news for the whole of the UK economy.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-09-11T12:42:46.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416367/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416367/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416367/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-09-04","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether he read the report, Shale Gas: Rural Economy Impacts, published by the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs in March 2014.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","9076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416368","Department for International Development","false","2015-09-11","<p>The UK supports a range of schemes that support disabled people in Ghana, including:</p><p> </p><ul><li>An education programme providing scholarships for girls, including those living with disabilities and girls whose parents/guardians live with disabilities.</li><li>A national cash transfer programme (the Livelihood Empowerment Against Poverty Programme), which also targets those with disabilities.</li><li>An entrepreneurship training/mentorship programme (Enhancing Growth in New Enterprises).</li><li>One of our larger civil society programmes, (Strengthening Transparency and Accountability Responsiveness) which supports initiatives that work with people with disabilities.We are also supporting improvements to the quality of mental health care through working with the relevant regulatory body (Mental Health Authority) and two large NGOs (BasicNeeds and Christian Health Association of Ghana) to increase access to better care. DFID in Ghana is also developing links with the UK International Citizen Service Volunteer programme which works with disabled groups in the North of Ghana.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID Ghana’s Operational Plan 2011-2016 (updated December 2014) sets out the UK’s current priorities for development assistance in Ghana, as agreed with the Ghanaian authorities. This can be accessed through <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfid-ghana-operational-plan-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dfid-ghana-operational-plan-2014</a>.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-09-11T12:01:59.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416368/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416368/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416368/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-09-04","Ghana: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support the UK is providing to disabled people in Ghana.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","8409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416369","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Inter-Ministerial Group will meet this winter and is expected to continue its focus, of using UK expertise to improve international animal welfare standards and combatting the illegal wildlife trade.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-09-11T11:23:00.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416369/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416369/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416369/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-09-04","International Animal Welfare Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the current priorities are for the Inter-Ministerial Group on International Animal Welfare; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","8416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416370","Department of Health","false","2015-09-11","<p>Wheelchair services are the responsibility of local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). No information is held centrally about the demand for short-term wheelchair loans, which are predominantly made by charities such as the Red Cross rather than by CCGs themselves.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>NHS England has recently established a new national wheelchair dataset, which went live from 1 July. This will enable the use of data in future to drive improvement in wheelchair services that are provided by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-09-11T11:12:43.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416370/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416370/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-04","Wheelchairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to Putting the wheels in motion: Assessing the value of British Red Cross short-term wheelchair loans, published by British Red Cross, July 2015, what assessment he has made of demand for short-term wheelchair loans.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","8538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416371","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-09-14","<p>My Department currently has no plans to publish employability league tables. Employability information is already published in a variety of ways and recent legislative changes will enable analysis of graduate earnings over a longer time period, thus providing a richer data set.</p><p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) publish provider-level comparisons of employability outcomes in the Higher Education Performance Indicators (<a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/pis/emp" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/pis/emp</a>). These are intended to be considered alongside the published benchmarks, which take account of the student entry profile and subject mix at each provider.</p><p>Information on graduate employment and salaries is also included in the Key Information Set (<a href="https://unistats.direct.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://unistats.direct.gov.uk</a>) to help university applicants choose the most suitable course and higher education provider.</p><p>Finally, employment outcomes are one of the measures we are considering for inclusion in the new Teaching Excellence Framework. We will consult on this later this Autumn.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-09-14T13:25:12.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416371/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416371/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-09-04","Graduates: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department plans to publish university course employability league tables.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","8571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416372","Department of Health","false","2015-09-14","<p>NHS Employers are currently working on detailed proposals for reformed contracts for consultants and for doctors and dentists in training. These proposals will be based on the recommendations made by the independent Review Body on Doctors’ and Dentists’ Remuneration in its report published in July 2015. The report can be found at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/contract-reform-for-consultants-and-doctors-and-dentists-in-training-supporting-healthcare-services-seven-days-a-week" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/contract-reform-for-consultants-and-doctors-and-dentists-in-training-supporting-healthcare-services-seven-days-a-week</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","8677","2015-09-14T16:05:38.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416372/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/416372/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-09-04","Doctors: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how he will classify residential and non-residential on call as part of his contract reform discussions with the medical profession.","true","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","8676"
